High-aspect-ratio (HAR) micro- and nanostructures on silicon (Si), e.g. deep holes and deep trenches, are major building blocks for advanced microelectronic systems. The depth of these HAR structures is much larger than their width or diameter. This feature imposes great challenge to their fabrication process. Until now, HAR structures on Si are fabricated by selective removal a certain volume of Si from Si substrates, a process generally referred to as Si etch. Traditionally fabrication methods for HAR structures incur high cost and suffer from low throughput. This project has developed fundamental understanding of a novel Si etch method, named metal-assisted chemical etching (MaCE), for fabrication of uniform HAR structures with order-of-magnitude lower cost as well as higher throughput. Five critical achievements are accomplished by the project:

(1)   The critical challenge of obtaining uniform HAR structures by MaCE is addressed where random etching are observed;

(2)   Suitable experimental conditions are presented, under which uniform HAR holes and trenches on Si are successfully fabricated;

(3)   Fundamental physicochemical processes that determines the uniformity of MaCE are elucidated by experimental data;

(4)   HAR structures with novel geometry are created by MaCE, which are difficult to be fabricated by existing methods;

(5)   The method is demonstrated to be compatible with current schematics of industry and applicable in high volume manufacturing.

The achievements broaden the fundamental knowledge in chemistry of metal-solution-semiconductor interface. The established method may revolutionize the manufacturing process of advanced microelectronic systems. These scientific discoveries mentioned above have been disseminated through 8 peer-reviewed journals, 10 conference proceedings and 1 US Patent Application. The project has supported education of 2 graduate and 3 undergraduate students through research experience. 



